        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular resolution of 1" is picked to minimize background confusion. We do not expect the disk to be resolved. The proposed observation can be carried out in any higher angular resolution. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This program aims to detect (or set a stringent limit on) the cold debris disk component accompanying the dynamically active and highly variable disk around the solar-like star ID8 in NGC 2547. At the distance of 400 pc, the expected disk angular size is too small to be resolved. Since we have no far-infrared data to constrain the disk properties, we design our observation based on what we know about the general disk behavior around stars in a similar age range. If the ID8 system has a "normal" cold disk, we expect the disk emission to be detected at S/N &gt;&gt;10 sigma. However, the system could have depleted its outer cold planetesimal belt. We derive a sensitivity, 11.3 uJy/beam at Band 7 with a total of on-source integration of 5 hours, if the cold disk is depleted. With such a sensitivity, a failure to detect the cold disk would be a very surprising result, and the stringent limit by the proposed ALMA observation will provide new insights into the nature of the young, active ID8 system. 

Band 7 is our best choice because it has the best sensitivity to detect cold (~100 to 50 K) dust  emission. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
