    <prp:abstract>This program aims to detect (or set a stringent limit on) the cold debris disk component accompanying the dynamically active and highly variable disk around the solar-like star ID8 in NGC 2547. The mid-infrared variability indicates frequent collisions among large asteroids and a high rate of mass loss from the inner zone of this planetary system. This behavior suggests the system is undergoing chaotic building of terrestrial planets or is experiencing a dynamic upset similar to the Late Heavy Bombardment. The emission of the to-date undetected cold component is our only avenue to explore the mass of the full disk system and to discover if the outer Kuiper-belt-like zone has been depleted in a manner similar to events in the early evolution of the Solar System.</prp:abstract>
